nodes.title: Regarding SAGS
widgets_values:
From : u/dotJack on reddit:

Scale works a lot like weight in your other favorite nodes or at least the effect is similar even though the internal implementation probably changes the size of the noise being applied or the amplitude of the noise. At lower numbers the applied noise just gets too fine/low contrast or too large to change anything. Perhaps the blur just evens it out at certain values.

Near 0.0 values lead to near-nothing changing in the image regardless of the blur_sigma value. I think some very minor changes are applied even at 0 but it's so incredibly minor that you couldn't tell which output has the node applied and which doesn't.

Once you go above 1, the image becomes a lot more crunchy and as you approach even higher numbers, there's a strong burn/over-processed effect, similar to what occurs with higher cfg values. If the blur_sigma is big enough, then the burn is a lot less pronounced.


Blur sigma

Blur sigma at 0.1 has almost no effect and 0 produces a black image.

At 0.5 and 1.0, the image grows a lot in contrast / sharpness and surface textures gain some fine details but at the same time the higher you go, the more you will lose variation and detail in the bigger shape of the edges.

A ripped piece of paper will have the rip become more linear as opposed to a random mountain-range.


sag_threshold (hidden input)
Someone in the GitHub pull request above asked about including a 'sag_threshold' widget to the node as an input. Internally this set to 1 and can't be changed but it's fairly straightforward to implement in the python code so I decided to try it out. The result was that it should just stay as 1.
Functionally I think this is like a different kind of inverse 'weight' parameter. I'm sure internally it sets a threshold above or below which the noise won't be or would be applied.
At 3ish and above, the image barely changes. At 2ish, there's changes but they're less obvious but you can compare the output images and you are able to tell which one has the node applied to it. At 1 you get the default behavior so everything described above applies.
As you approach 0, the effects above get a lot more obvious. The output loses almost all of it's realism/whatever style it's generated it and becomes a weird soft dreamlike ... thing but not in any kind of good way in my opinion.

Feel free to experiment with it, the python code is not difficult to augment, find all the places that mention blur_sigma and scale and add add the seg_threshold parameter if it's there already. If it is there already, change the way it's implemented to match the lines referencing scale and/or blur_sigma

It's not an effect I'd ever want to apply to images so I won't be keeping this parameter in my local node but it IS there and it does change the image.

nodes.title: FreeU_V2 recommended
widgets_values:
OFFICIAL SDXL: b1: 1.3, b2: 1.4, s1: 0.9, s2: 0.2

b1: 1  b1  1.2
b2: 1.2  b2  1.6
s1: s1  1
s2: s2  1

** DETAILS ** (tx to /u/siberian-duck)
Neutral value for all FreeU options b1, b2, s1 and s2 is 1. Not unexpected, but as they are not the default values in the node, I mention it here.

b1: responsible for the larger areas on the image
b2: responsible for the smaller areas on the image
s1: responsible for the details in b2
s2: responsible for the details in b1

So s1 belongs to b2 and s1 to b2. The numbers 1 and 2 are misleading.

b1 and b2 with a value lower than 1 causes artefacts, like missing last sample steps (noisy image).

Every value over 1 increases overall contrast and saturation of colors but with emphasis of their area of responsibility.

If you think of an upper body portrait with a blurry background:

b1: background, even skin
b2: clothes, bigger areas of hair, eye brows, eyes, nose, mouth
s1: tiniest details, like hair on the skin, iris, finest skin structure, fabric fibers
s2: small details like skin and clothes structure

Increasing...
...b1 increases contrast and causes lost of small details, but tiny details don't get lost
...b2 increases contrast and causes lost of tiny details, but small details don't get lost
...s1 increases contrast and tiny details
...s1 increases contrast and small details

Decreasing...
...b1 causes artefacts (lower than 1)
...b2 causes artefacts (lower than 1)
...s1 causes lost of tiny details without losing contrast (dreamy look)
...s2 causes lost of small details without losing contrast (elegant, still realtic beauty look)

** DISCLAIMER **
This worfklow is provided 'AS IS' and is not supported in ANY way by the author. I am not responsible if the installation of custom nodes breaks your comfyUI install, or for anything for that matter.
If you have technical issues with nodes, please check the github for respective nodes - they get updated almost every day in some cases, and may not behave the same on windows/linux/mac etc. 
Each node used here is the property of their respective author - and they may contain non-commercial clauses.


** PURPOSE **
To create a video generation engine that adds a lot of detail on the upscale stage, can generate sequences, and can be invoked in sequence to create meaningful scenes for storytelling. This will be released in phases due to the very large scope of the project.


** USAGE ** 
0. Watch the tuturial video(s) posted on my YT channel (https://www.youtube.com/@stephantual)
1. Start by generating a zeroscope stage 1 video, iterate until you're happy. This could take dozens of prompts and dozens of seeds. 2. If you are low vram, use zeroscope stage 2 with a model from opendb. Which one you select depends on your subject: remacri is good for most things if you're not going for 'pixel perfect'. 
3. If you do have high vram (24 and above), use SUPIR *INSTEAD* of stage 2. Seriously - it's so much better - technically you're simply using diffusion using sdxl , adding details to the image. 
4. Now you can upscale to remove the 'jitter'. I tried everything - my favorite is using AD + LCM or Lightning (depending on your subject/aestetic/source). I tested for days and found Ultimate SD upscaler gives better results than upscaling the latent first. Hence, it's implemented that way. 
5. On controlnets: only use them if your final denoise is sky high, ie. you're going for artistic effects. I only used this for upscaling 'photorealistic', so i keep my denoise low.
6. Experiment! this is to learn, not an "app" :)
